SIMPLE: outlandish
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Outlandish
<hw>Out*land"ish</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>⟦umac⟧tlendisc</ets> foreign. See <er>Out</er>, <er>Land</er>, and
<er>-ish</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Foreign; not native.</def>
<mark>[archaic]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Him did <qex>outlandish</qex> women cause to sin.</q>
<rj><qau>Neh. xiii. 26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Its barley water and its <qex>outlandish</qex> wines.</q>
<rj><qau>G. W. Cable.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>Deviating conspicuously from
common practice; strange; freakish; bizarre; rude; barbarous; uncouth;
clownish; <as>as, an <ex>outlandish</ex> dress, behavior, or
speech</as>; -- usually used in a negative sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Something <qex>outlandish</qex>, unearthy, or at variance with
ordinary fashion.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>--<wordforms><wf>Out*land"ish*ly</wf>,
<pos>adv.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>outlandishness</ent>⟦br⟧
